{"parse":{"title":"Herbert Parker (scientist)","pageid":40663198,"revid":723607307,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Herbert M. Parker</b> (13 April 1910, <a href=\"/wiki/Accrington\" title=\"Accrington\">Accrington</a> \u2013 5 March 1984, <a href=\"/wiki/Richland,_Washington\" title=\"Richland, Washington\">Richland, Washington</a>) was an English, and American immigrant, medical physicist. He was a pioneer of medical radiation therapy and radiation safety, known for introducing the <a href=\"/wiki/R%C3%B6ntgen_equivalent_physical\" title=\"R\u00f6ntgen equivalent physical\">roentgen equivalent physical (rep)</a>, the forerunner of the <a href=\"/wiki/Gray_(unit)\" title=\"Gray (unit)\">gray</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Rad_(unit)\" title=\"Rad (unit)\">rad</a>, and also the roentgen equivalent biological (reb), the forerunner of the <a href=\"/wiki/R%C3%B6ntgen_equivalent_man\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"R\u00f6ntgen equivalent man\">rem</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Sievert\" title=\"Sievert\">sievert</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Career\">Career</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Herbert_Parker_(scientist)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Career\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>After receiving an M.S. in physics from the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Manchester\" title=\"University of Manchester\">University of Manchester</a> in 1931, Parker became a medical physicist at the <a href=\"/wiki/Christie_Hospital\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Christie Hospital\">Christie Hospital</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Christie_Hospital#Foundation_of_the_Holt_Institute\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Christie Hospital\">Holt Radium Institute</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Manchester\" title=\"Manchester\">Manchester</a>. With James R. Paterson, he developed in 1932 the Paterson-Parker method, or Manchester System, for radiation therapy. The method allows physicians to use radium needles or tubes to maximize the radiation dose delivered to a cancerous tumour whilst minimizing the dose to healthy tissue.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> In 1938 Parker immigrated to the U.S.A. to begin work at the <a href=\"/wiki/Swedish_Medical_Center\" title=\"Swedish Medical Center\">Swedish Hospital</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Seattle\" title=\"Seattle\">Seattle</a>,  where he worked with the radiologist Simeon T. Cantril on Supervoltage Therapy research at the Tumor Institute. In 1942 Parker went to the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago</a> to work on the <a href=\"/wiki/Manhattan_Project\" title=\"Manhattan Project\">Manhattan Project</a> at the \u201cMetallurgical Laboratory.\u201d In 1943 he went to <a href=\"/wiki/Oak_Ridge_National_Laboratory\" title=\"Oak Ridge National Laboratory\">Oak Ridge National Laboratory</a> to establish the health physics program for the U.S. atomic energy program. In 1944 Parker returned to the state of Washington to initiate the health physics program at the <a href=\"/wiki/Hanford_Site\" title=\"Hanford Site\">Hanford Laboratories</a>. In 1947 he became manager of operations and research in radiological science. In 1956 he was promoted to become the overall manager at the Hanford Laboratories, holding this position until 1965 when operation of Hanford Laboratories was transferred from <a href=\"/wiki/General_Electric_Corporation\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"General Electric Corporation\">GE</a> to <a href=\"/wiki/Battelle_Memorial_Institute\" title=\"Battelle Memorial Institute\">Battelle Memorial Institute</a>.\n</p><p>Working with <a href=\"/wiki/James_Ralston_Kennedy_Paterson\" title=\"James Ralston Kennedy Paterson\">James Ralston Kennedy Paterson</a>, developed the Paterson-Parker rules for the <i>Radium Dosage System</i> also known as the Manchester system.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Honors\">Honors</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Herbert_Parker_(scientist)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Honors\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In 1978 Parker was elected to the National Academy of Engineering. He was made a Fellow of the American Physical Society and of the British Institute of Physics. He received in 1955 the <a href=\"/wiki/Henry_Harrington_Janeway#The_Janeway_Medal_and_Lectures\" title=\"Henry Harrington Janeway\">Janeway Medal</a> of the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Radium_Society\" title=\"American Radium Society\">American Radium Society</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Herbert_Parker_(scientist)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Kathren, Ronald L. (July 1984). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.physicstoday.org/resource/1/phtoad/v37/i7/p85_s1?bypassSSO=1\">\"Obituary: Herbert M. Parker\"</a>. <i>Physics Today</i>. <b>37</b> (7): 85. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1063/1.2916337\">10.1063/1.2916337</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Physics+Today&amp;rft.atitle=Obituary%3A+Herbert+M.+Parker&amp;rft.volume=37&amp;rft.issue=7&amp;rft.pages=85&amp;rft.date=1984-07&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1063%2F1.2916337&amp;rft.au=Kathren%2C+Ronald+L.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.physicstoday.org%2Fresource%2F1%2Fphtoad%2Fv37%2Fi7%2Fp85_s1%3FbypassSSO%3D1&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHerbert+Parker+%28scientist%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">\"Herbert M. Parker\". <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.nap.edu/openbook/0309039398/html/278-283.htm\"><i>Memorial Tributes from National Academy of Engineering</i></a>. National Academies Press. 1989. pp.&#160;278\u2013283.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Herbert+M.+Parker&amp;rft.btitle=Memorial+Tributes+from+National+Academy+of+Engineering&amp;rft.pages=278-283&amp;rft.pub=National+Academies+Press&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nap.edu%2Fopenbook%2F0309039398%2Fhtml%2F278-283.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHerbert+Parker+%28scientist%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite